  "prompt": "Why have so many professional wrestlers died young?",
  "response": "The unfortunate reality is that many professional wrestlers have died young due to a combination of factors. Some of the main reasons include:\n\n1. **Physical Toll**: Wrestling is an extremely physically demanding profession. The constant strain on the body can lead to injuries, chronic pain, and long-term health issues, which can contribute to a shortened lifespan.\n\n2. **Substance Abuse**: Many wrestlers have struggled with addiction to painkillers, steroids, and other substances. The use of these substances can lead to severe health problems, including heart disease, liver failure, and overdose.\n\n3. **Mental Health**: The intense lifestyle and pressure of being a professional wrestler can take a toll on mental health. Depression, anxiety, and other mental health issues are common, and if left untreated, can lead to tragic outcomes.\n\n4. **Lack of Healthcare**: Historically, many wrestlers did not have access to adequate healthcare or were hesitant to seek medical attention due to the fear of losing their jobs. This can result in untreated injuries and illnesses that worsen over time.\n\n5. **Lifestyle Factors**: The hectic travel schedule, irregular eating habits, and high-stress environment can contribute to poor health choices and a higher risk of health problems.\n\nIt's important to note that not all wrestlers face these issues, and many have gone on to live long and healthy lives. However, these factors have contributed to the sadly high number of wrestlers who have died young.",
